text:
I think it does apply to residential but sadly what I found after trying that in another life is that a good chunk of residential builders (and designers) worry more about the next job vs. the current one and they turn to VR as a marketing tool. Also not enough BIM penetration in smaller residential for these workflows to be seamless yet. The conversation usually goes "oh I need a 3D model?"

that said, the stakes are a lot higher on the larger projects we work on right now. A design mistake on residential is an unhappy resident. A design mistake in a water treatment plant means no clean drinking water.

My hope is for all buildings to align with the end user's functional needs, but have to start where the money is aka where the stakes are higher.

cast.text:
Why don't we count replies in the rewards score?

> it would be nice if engaging replies factor into warpcast rewards so that conversations are incentivized (instead of top-casts only)

1. Inbound replies do count, i.e. you cast a banger and a bunch of people reply. That's engagement. The rewards algo rewards engagement across inbound replies, likes, recasts, quote casts.

2. Replying to other people does not currently count. A few practical reasons: the average top-level cast gets way more engagement than the average reply (which usually gets engagement from the original cast author). There are exceptions, of course—especially if the reply is funny, i.e. a ratio.

3. We can consider adding replies, but even if we do that—and get more aggressive at surfacing replies in home feeds, top-level casting is still going to be the best way to get the most aggregate engagement.

4. Worth point out: there have been a few metas on Farcaster that rewarded replies. And then people complained about too many replies.

Spitballing here: Cast Protocol

I think it's good to create a distinction between your client and the protocol but still having a bridge between the brands. Farcaster and Warpcast were close but also different so it got confusing. 

Interestingly most clients tend to gravitate towards using Cast (Supercast, Herocast, Recaster, etc.) that it feels like "cast" is the brand devs think about at the protocol level.

Meanwhile non-client ecosystem apps tend to play with Far. Farcade, FarQuest, FarMarket.

Far is the front End.
Cast is the back end. 

Reminds me of Git, GitHub, GitLab, etc.

3. Every mint contributes to the prize pool and the first user to evolve into the Single Green Higher Arrow will be able to claim the prize pool

4. Try to selectively combine Arrows to win the prize or just mint and combine arrows to create an Arrow that you love
